   The notation `Subtype.val '' S` represents the image of the set `S` under the function `Subtype.val`. `Subtype.val` is the function that extracts the value from a `Subtype α` (which is `α` itself). So, `Subtype.val '' S` is just `S` if `S` is already a set of values, or it's the set `{Subtype.val x | x ∈ S}` if `S` is a set of `Subtype α` elements.

   The notation `Subtype.val ⁻¹' X` is the preimage of the set `X` under `Subtype.val`. Since `Subtype.val` is the identity function on the values, `Subtype.val ⁻¹' X` is just `X`.

   So, `Subtype.val '' (Subtype.val ⁻¹' symmDiff A (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B))` simplifies to `Subtype.val '' (symmDiff A (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B))`, which is just `symmDiff A (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B)`.

   Similarly, `Subtype.val '' (Subtype.val ⁻¹' symmDiff B (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B))` simplifies to `symmDiff B (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B)`.

   Therefore, `hAB` simplifies to `symmDiff A (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B) = symmDiff B (⋂ B ∈ 𝓒, B)`.

3. `this` is an equality between two sets:
