We need to show that for two sets `A, B ∈ C`, if `A ∩ C ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B = B ∩ C ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B`, then `A = B`.

But `A ∩ C = A` since `A ∈ C`. Similarly, `B ∩ C = B`.

Therefore, we have `A ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B = B ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B`.

But `A = (A \ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) ∪ (A ∩ ⋂ B ∈ C, B)`.

Similarly, `B = (B \ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) ∪ (B ∩ ⋂ B ∈ C, B)`.

So, we have `A \ ⋂ B ∈ C, B = (A ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) \ (A ∩ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) = (B ∆ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) \ (A ∩ ⋂ B ∈ C, B) = B \ ⋂ B ∈ C, B`.

